            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leo Valerio is a product of San Francisco's fog-laced Sunset District, the son of a city maintenance worker and a school secretary. Raised in a modest row house, his childhood was defined by the rhythm of the N Judah streetcar and a deep, unspoken appreciation for the civil servants who kept the city running. This working-class upbringing instilled in him a powerful sense of civic duty, a belief that policy wasn't abstract, but something that fixed potholes and funded after-school programs.\n\nHe enrolled at San Francisco State University, naturally drawn to Public Policy. He was an idealistic student, energized by theories of social equity and urban planning. His trajectory was altered during his junior year when his father suffered a debilitating back injury on the job. Leo left school to work full-time, helping his family navigate the labyrinth of workers' compensation and mounting medical bills. This raw, frustrating experience became his true education.\n\nDriven by this new, personal understanding of systemic flaws, Leo secured an internship with a City Supervisor. He lacked a degree, but his passion, grit, and intimate knowledge of the city's neighborhoods made him indispensable. The internship evolved into his current role as a legislative aide. At 30, he\u2019s a veteran of City Hall\u2019s corridors, respected for his tireless work ethic and ability to connect with constituents.\n\nToday, Leo lives in a small, tidy apartment in Hayes Valley, a 2.8-mile Muni ride from his office. His day begins with the rumble of the bus and ends late, poring over policy drafts. His social life consists of a tight-knit circle of high school friends and weekly dinners with his parents in the Sunset. He\u2019s deeply connected to his city, feeling the weight of its housing crisis and homeless emergency as a personal responsibility.\n\nLeo\u2019s quiet aspiration isn\u2019t to run for office himself, but to one day shepherd a landmark piece of legislation\u2014perhaps reforming municipal healthcare or workers' rights\u2014that would prevent other families from enduring what his did. He is a steward of his hometown, fighting not for power, but for the soul of the San Francisco that raised him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, watching his father in his heavy city-issued jacket disappear into the pre-dawn fog of the Sunset. The rumble of the N Judah was his alarm clock. He knew his dad was one of the people who kept the city\u2019s heart beating, fixing the tracks and signals others took for granted. That quiet pride became the bedrock of his worldview: that the most vital work is often the most invisible. He decided early he wanted to be one of the unseen people who cared.\n\n2.\nAt 20, he remembers sitting at the Sunset kitchen table, a denied workers\u2019 comp form under his hands. His mom was on the phone, her voice strained. In the next room, his father\u2019s pained groan was a constant, low rumble. The city his dad helped build felt like a cold, bureaucratic wall. The abstract theories from his policy classes dissolved into a hot, helpless anger. It wasn\u2019t a matter of ideology anymore; it was a promise made to his family to tear down that wall.\n\n3.\nHe was 19, a sophomore at SF State, feeling exhilarated after a late-night debate about urban planning theory. Walking to the M train, he saw the city as a fascinating puzzle box he could solve with the right ideas and data. Policy felt clean, academic, a noble intellectual pursuit. He now looks back on that version of himself with a gentle ache\u2014the idealistic boy who believed in perfect systems, before he learned they are made of people and are just as fragile and flawed.\n\n4.\nIn his first year as an aide, around age 24, a frantic call came from an elderly woman whose building's heat had been broken for a week in December. He spent the next 48 hours relentlessly pushing city agencies and the landlord. When he finally got the call back from her, her voice thick with relief, saying the heat was on, he felt a powerful, grounding click. This was it. This was policy made real, a tangible piece of warmth and safety he had secured for someone.\n\n5.\nJust last Sunday, at the weekly dinner at his parents\u2019 house. His father shifted in his chair, a familiar, subtle movement to ease the chronic ache in his back. In that small, silent gesture, Leo saw his entire mission. It was the reason for the late nights in his Hayes Valley apartment and the endless drafts. The city\u2019s problems weren\u2019t abstract headlines; they were sitting right across from him, asking him to pass the potatoes. It was all the fuel he needed for the week ahead."
